% signal=squid

\startcomponent excursion-en-math

\enablemode[**en-us]

\project excursion

\startchapter[title=Typesetting math,reference={mathematics,formulas}]

\startsection[title=Introduction]

\index {math}

\Command{\tex{m}}
\Command{\tex{im}}
\Command{\tex{dm}}
\Command{\tex{startformula}}
\Command{\tex{definereferenceformat}}
\Command{\tex{startnamedmatrix}}
\Command{\tex{startmathmatrix}}
\Command{\tex{mtext}}
\Command{\tex{texthere}}
\Command{\tex{startcases}}
\Command{\tex{setupmathoperators}}
\Command{\tex{setupmathradical}}

In this section we spend a large number of pages on math because \CONTEXT\ is
based on \TEX\ which is famous for its math typesetting. If math is not your
thing and you don't need it in your document you can always skip this section.

The math environment used by \CONTEXT\ has been overhauled completely. There have
been a great number of improvements, sometimes leading also to a changed way of
coding math in \CONTEXT. It is beyond this manual to go into the depth of the
possibilities and the details. We advise you to do some further reading on
typesetting formulas with \CONTEXT\ in \goto{\Emph{Mathematics in \CONTEXT}}[url
(manual:mathematics)] written by Mikael Sundqvist and Hans Hagen. The following
pages are completely derived from the afore mentioned manual.

\stopsection

\startsection[title=Typesetting math]

\index {math mode}
\index {display mode}
\index {text mode}

Normally different conventions are applied for typesetting normal text and math
text. These conventions are \quote{known} by \CONTEXT\ \LMTX\ and applied
accordingly when generating a document. We can rely on \CONTEXT\ \LMTX\ for
delivering high quality math output.

\startsubsection[title=Conventions]

A number of conventions for math are:

\startitemize[n,packed]

  \startitem
    Characters are typeset in \m{math\ italic} (don't confuse this with the
    normal {\it italic characters} in a text font).
  \stopitem

  \startitem
    Symbols like Greek characters (\m{\alpha}, \m{\chi}) and math symbols
    (\m{\leq}, \m{\geq}, \m{\in}) are used.
  \stopitem

  \startitem
    Spacing will differ from normal spacing.
  \stopitem

  \startitem
    Math expressions have a different alignment than running text.
  \stopitem

  \startitem
    The sub- and superscripts are downsized automatically, like in \m{a^{b}_{c}}.
  \stopitem

  \startitem
	 Certain symbols have different appearances in the inline and display mode.
  \stopitem

\stopitemize

\stopsubsection

\startsubsection[title=Math modes]

When typesetting math you have to work in the so called math mode in which math
expressions can be defined in \CONTEXT. Math mode has two alternatives: text mode
(inline math) and display mode (displayed math). Math in text mode can be
activated by \type{\im}, while display mode is activated by \type{\dm}. These
commands are rather simple and replace basically the old \type{$ ... $} and
\type{$$ ... $$} commands. Although the latter commands still work in \CONTEXT\
it is discouraged to use them anymore. A better command for inline math
typesetting is: \type{\m} allowing for giving some optional arguments with the
command.

\startbuffer
\m[color=blue]{a^2 + b^2 = c^2}
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

This becomes after type setting: \getbuffer

In \CONTEXT\ displayed math is activated with the \type{\startformula ...
\stopformula} command pair in order to have more grip on vertical spacing around
the formula. The use of \type{{}} (grouping) in mathematical expressions are
essential for separating operations in a given formula.

There are naturally three different sizes used in math, as seen in \m {a ^ {b ^
c}}. You usually do not have to care about this, but if you want to enforce the
size in sub/superscripts you can use \type{\scriptstyle} and if you want to
enforce the size in the next level, use \type{\scriptscriptstyle}.

Symbols like \type{\int} \m{\int} and \type{\sum} \m{\sum} will have a different
form in text and display mode. If we type \type {\m{\sum_{n=1}^{m}}} or \type
{\m{\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}}} we will get {\m{\sum_{n=1}^{m}}} and
{\m{\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}}}. But when you type:

\startbuffer
\startformula
  \sum_{n=1}^{m} \quad \mtext{and} \quad
  \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

to get display mode, you get:

\getbuffer

In the previous examples super- and subscripts are used. For superscript the
caret (^) is used and for subscript the underscore (_) is applied. If a super- or
subscript is more than one character long, grouping with \type{{}} is required.

\stopsubsection

\startsubsection[title=Fractions]

For typesetting fractions there is the command \type {\frac} which takes two
arguments the numerator and the denominator. For\space \m{{\frac{a}{1+b}}+c} we
type for instance \type {\m{\frac{a}{1+b}+c}}. The \type{\frac} command has a
couple of siblings. \type{\dfrac}, \type{\tfrac}, \type{\sfrac} which force
display size, text size and script size respectively. There is also \type{\vfrac}
which replaces the horizontal dividing bar into a slanted bar.

\startbuffer
\startformula
  \frac{a}{b} = \dfrac{a}{b}
              = \tfrac{a}{b}
              = \sfrac{a}{b}
              = \vfrac{a}{b}
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

The \type{\vfrac} version looks sometimes better in running text \m{\vfrac{a}{b}}
or in situations where a fraction occurs inside another fraction.

\startbuffer
\startformula
  a_0+{\frac{a}{a_1+\frac{1}{a_2}}}
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

\page[bigpreference]

but prefer:

\startbuffer
\startformula
  a_0 + {\frac{a}{a_1 + \vfrac{1}{a_2}}}
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

to obtain:

\getbuffer

\stopsubsection

\startsubsection[title=Fences]

Fences, also known as paired delimiters, are a pair of symbols to visually group
parts of a mathematical expression.

\startbuffer
\startformula
  \fenced[parenthesis] {1 + \frac{a}{b}} \mtp{}
  \fenced[bracket]     {F(x)^2}_a^b      \mtp{}
  \fenced[brace]       {\frac{x}{n}}     \mtp{}
  \fenced[angle]       {f ,g}
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

Another possibility is to use the traditional fencing commands \type{\left} and
\type{\right}:

\startbuffer
\startformula
  \left( 1 + \frac{a}{b}   \right)       \mtp{}
  \left[ F(x)^2            \right]_a^b   \mtp{}
  \left{ \frac{x}{n}       \right}       \mtp{}
  \left\langle f, g        \right\rangle
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

Further aspects of fences are discussed in the manual \goto{\Emph{Mathematics in
\CONTEXT}}[url (manual:mathematics)].

\stopsubsection

\page[bigpreference]

\startsubsection[title=Matrices]

For presenting a simple matrix one can use

\startbuffer
\startformula
  \startmathmatrix
    \NC a \NC b \NR
    \NC c \NC d \NR
  \stopmathmatrix
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

\page[bigpreference]

Often such matrices are surrounded with fences

\startbuffer
\startformula
  \startmathmatrix[fences=bracket]
    \NC a \NC b \NR
    \NC c \NC d \NR
  \stopmathmatrix
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

A number of fenced matrices are predefined. Using those looks as follows:

\startbuffer
\startformula
  \startnamedmatrix[matrix:bars]
    \NC a \NC b \NR
    \NC c \NC d \NR
  \stopnamedmatrix
  =
  \bmatrix{a,b;c,d}
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

The predefined fences for \type{\startnamedmatrix ... \stopnamedmatrix} are
summarized in \in{table}[tab:matrix-fences]. As shown in the a forehead shown
example there are \quote{simple commands} giving in the similar results than with
the full commands. They save typing but do not add to the readability of the
code.

\startplacetable
  [location=here,
   reference=tab:matrix-fences,
   title={Predefined named matrix fences}]
   \bTABLE
     \bTR \bTD Instance           \eTD \bTD Simple command \eTD \eTR
     \bTR \bTD matrix:bars        \eTD \bTD vmatrix        \eTD \eTR
     \bTR \bTD matrix:braces      \eTD \bTD bracematrix    \eTD \eTR
     \bTR \bTD matrix:brackets    \eTD \bTD bmatrix        \eTD \eTR
     \bTR \bTD matrix:doublebar   \eTD \bTD vvmatrix       \eTD \eTR
     \bTR \bTD matrix:groups      \eTD \bTD gmatrix        \eTD \eTR
     \bTR \bTD matrix:none        \eTD \bTD  matrix        \eTD \eTR
     \bTR \bTD matrix parentheses \eTD \bTD pmatrix        \eTD \eTR
     \bTR \bTD matrix:triplebar   \eTD \bTD vvvmatrix      \eTD \eTR
   \eTABLE
\stopplacetable

\stopsubsection

%\doifmode{Book}{\page[yes]}

\startsubsection[title=Accents]

There is a set of accents predefined. They can be put on top of characters e.g. \type{\acute{x}}~\m{\acute{x}}. \in{Table}[tab:accents] shows the details.

\startplacetable
  [location=here,
   reference=tab:accents,
   title={Math accents}]
  \switchtobodyfont[9pt]
  \bTABLE
    \setupTABLE[c][2,4,6][style=math,align=middle]
    \bTR
      \bTD Symbol name \eTD \bTD Typeset symbol \eTD
      \bTD Symbol name \eTD \bTD Typeset symbol \eTD
    \eTR
    \bTR
      \bTD \type{\grave} \eTD \bTD \m{\grave{x}} \eTD
  	  \bTD \type{\acute} \eTD \bTD \m{\acute{x}} \eTD
    \eTR
    \bTR
      \bTD \type{\hat  } \eTD \bTD \m{\hat  {x}} \eTD
      \bTD \type{\tilde} \eTD \bTD \m{\tilde{x}} \eTD
    \eTR
    \bTR
  	  \bTD \type{\bar  } \eTD \bTD \m{\bar  {x}} \eTD
  	  \bTD \type{\breve} \eTD \bTD \m{\breve{x}} \eTD
    \eTR
    \bTR
      \bTD \type{\dot }  \eTD \bTD \m{\dot  {x}} \eTD
      \bTD \type{\ddot}  \eTD \bTD \m{\ddot {x}} \eTD
    \eTR
    \bTR
      \bTD \type{\dddot}  \eTD \bTD \m{ \dddot{x}} \eTD
      \bTD \type{\ddddot} \eTD \bTD \m{\ddddot{x}} \eTD
    \eTR
    \bTR
  	  \bTD \type{\ring}  \eTD \bTD \m{\ring {x}} \eTD
      \bTD \type{\check} \eTD \bTD \m{\check{x}} \eTD
    \eTR
    \bTR
      \bTD \type{\overleftharpoon}  \eTD \bTD \m{\overleftharpoon{x}}  \eTD
      \bTD \type{\overrightharpoon} \eTD \bTD \m{\overrightharpoon{x}} \eTD
    \eTR
  \eTABLE
\stopplacetable

When an accent has to be covering more than one character we have the so called
wide variants as given in \in{table}[tab:wideaccents].

\startplacetable
  [location=here,
	 reference=tab:wideaccents,
