\startsection[title=Displayed math]

\startsubsection[title=Simple formulas]

An example of a simple formula is

\startbuffer
  \startformula
    \sum _ {k = 1} ^ n k = \frac {n(n + 1)}{2}
  \stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

\stopsubsection

\startsubsection[title=Chain formulas]

Alignment in math expressions may need special attention. In multi line
expressions we sometimes need to align at the equal sign.

\startbuffer
\startformula
  ax^2 + Bx +c \alignhere = 0
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\startbuffer
\startformula
  2\int __ {-1} ^^ {1} \sqrt {1 - t ^ 2} \dd t
  \alignhere
  =
  2\int __ {-\pi/2} ^^ {\pi/2} \cos ^ 2 x \dd x
  \breakhere
  =
  \int __ {-\pi/2} ^^ {\pi/2} 1 + \cos 2x \dd x
  \breakhere
  = \pi.
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

A different, and often more compact approach, is to typeset the formulas not
aligned, but the first one flushed left, the last one flushed right and the rest
of them midaligned. This can be done by using \type{align=slanted}.

\stopsubsection

\startsubsection[title=Multiple formulas]

Punctuation in math has to be considered. There is a section explaining this in
\goto{\Emph{Mathematics in \CONTEXT}}[url(manual:mathematics)] for reference.

\startbuffer
 \im{f(x)=\sin x}, \im{x\in\reals}
\stopbuffer

In inline math writing \type{\im{f(x)=\sin x}, \im{x\in\reals}}, we get
\getbuffer. The point is, that the comma between the two formulas is taken from
the text font. In order to achieve this in displayed math \type{\mtp} (math text
punctuation) is used:

\startbuffer
\startformula
  f(x) = \sin x \mtp{,}
  x \in \reals  \mtp{.}
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

The following three formulas fit easily in one line and then it is the preferred
way of showing them:

\startbuffer
\startformula
  x = r \sin\theta \cos\phi \mtp{,}
  y = r \sin\theta \sin\phi \mtp{,}
  z = r \cos\theta          \mtp{.}
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

However one can easily stack several formulas on top of each other with

\startbuffer
\startformula
  x = r \sin\theta \cos\phi \mtp{,} \breakhere
  y = r \sin\theta \sin\phi \mtp{,} \breakhere
  z = r \cos\theta          \mtp{.}
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

When alignment should be enforced, this can best be done on the first equal sign

\startbuffer
\startformula
  x \alignhere = r \sin\theta \cos\phi \mtp{,} \breakhere
  y \alignhere = r \sin\theta \sin\phi \mtp{,} \breakhere
  z \alignhere = r \cos\theta          \mtp{.}
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

The old method of aligning with \type{\startalign...\stopalign} is still in place
and can be used:

\startbuffer
\startformula
  \startalign
    \NC x \EQ r \sin\theta \cos\phi \mtp{,} \NR
    \NC y \EQ r \sin\theta \sin\phi \mtp{,} \NR
    \NC z \EQ r \cos\theta          \mtp{.} \NR
  \stopalign
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

 \typebuffer

 \getbuffer

\stopsubsection

\page[bigpreference]

\startsubsection[title=Cases]

Math cases have a lot of options. You can define your one versions with

\shortsetup{definemathcases}

and influence the appearance with

\shortsetup{setupmathcases}

An example dealing with the possibility to have enlarged (display style) formulas
could look like this

\startbuffer
\definemathcases
  [Mynewcases]
  [cases]
  [mathstyle=display]
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

\startbuffer
\startformula
  \frac{1}{2} \int f(x) \alignhere =
  \startcases
    \NC  \frac{1}{2} \int \NC x \geq 0 \NR
    \NC -\frac{1}{2} \int \NC x <    0 \NR
  \stopcases
  \breakhere =
  \startMynewcases
    \NC  \frac{1}{2} \int \NC x \geq 0 \NR
    \NC -\frac{1}{2} \int \NC x <    0 \NR
  \stopMynewcases
\stopformula
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

\stopsubsection

\startsubsection[title=Equation labels]

\CONTEXT\ always offered the possibility to label equations automatically. This
is done by using:

\startbuffer
\startplaceformula
  [reference=eq:Pythagoras]
  \startformula
    a^2 + b^2 = c^2
  \stopformula
\stopplaceformula

From \in{Equation}[eq:Pythagoras] it follows \unknown
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

There is nothing new to the method of referencing the equation (see also in
\in{chapter}[chap:reference]). However unlike the number style of the equation
between parentheses the reference in the text show only the number. To change
this one can define a new referencing command

\shortsetup{definereferenceformat}

\startbuffer
\definereferenceformat
  [Eqref]
  [left=(,
   right=)]
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

We now can use the \type{\Eqref}:\type{ From \Eqref{equation }[eq:pythagoras]
follows \unknown}

From \Eqref{equation }[eq:Pythagoras] follows \unknown

If there is a number of formulas combined into a set, each formula can have its
own number and also its own reference. You do not need to use
\type{\startplaceformula ... \stopplaceformula} in this case.

\startbuffer
\startformula
  x \alignhere = r \sin\theta \cos\phi \mtp{,}
    \numberhere[eq:xa] \breakhere
  y \alignhere = r \sin\theta \sin\phi \mtp{,}
    \numberhere[eq:ya]\breakhere
  z \alignhere = r \cos\theta          \mtp{.}
    \numberhere[eq:za]
\stopformula


In \Eqref{equations }[eq:xa], \Eqref{}[eq:ya] and
\Eqref{}[eq:za] we see \unknown
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

With the alternative alignment command it would look as follows. Note that the
reference is attached to the new line command \type{\NR}. Using this method of
coding the use of \type{\startplaceformula ... \stopplaceformula} is needed:

\startbuffer
\startplaceformula
  \startformula
    \startalign
      \NC x \EQ r \sin\theta \cos\phi \mtp{,} \NR[eq:xb]
      \NC y \EQ r \sin\theta \sin\phi \mtp{,} \NR[eq:yb]
      \NC z \EQ r \cos\theta          \mtp{.} \NR[eq:zb]
    \stopalign
  \stopformula
\stopplaceformula


In \Eqref{equations }[eq:xb], \Eqref{}[eq:yb]
and \Eqref{}[eq:zb] we see \unknown
\stopbuffer

 \typebuffer

 \getbuffer

In case that sub-numbering is asked for one can use:

\startbuffer
\startformula
  \startsubnumberinghere
    x \alignhere = r \sin\theta \cos\phi \mtp{,}
      \numberhere[eq:xc] \breakhere
    y \alignhere = r \sin\theta \sin\phi \mtp{,}
      \numberhere[eq:yc]\breakhere
    z \alignhere = r \cos\theta          \mtp{.}
    \numberhere[eq:zc]
  \stopsubnumberinghere
\stopformula

In \Eqref{equations }[eq:xc], \Eqref{}[eq:yc]
and \Eqref{}[eq:zc] we see \unknown
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

\startbuffer
\startplaceformula[eq:spheres]
  \startformula
    \startalign
      \NC x \EQ r \sin\theta \cos\phi \mtp{,} \NR[+]
      \NC y \EQ r \sin\theta \sin\phi \mtp{,} \NR[+]
      \NC z \EQ r \cos\theta          \mtp{.} \NR[+]
    \stopalign
  \stopformula
\stopplaceformula

We see in \Eqref{equation }[eq:spheres] \unknown
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

Obviously the reference is to the whole set of equations, therefore we get the
equation number only. If we need to refer to the single equations the coding
becomes:

\startbuffer
\startplaceformula
  \startformula
    \startalign
      \NC x \EQ r \sin\theta \cos\phi \mtp{,} \NR[eq:xd]
      \NC y \EQ r \sin\theta \sin\phi \mtp{,} \NR[eq:yd]
      \NC z \EQ r \cos\theta          \mtp{.} \NR[eq:zd]
    \stopalign
  \stopformula
\stopplaceformula

In \Eqref{equations }[eq:xd], \Eqref{}[eq:yd]
and \Eqref{}[eq:zd] we see \unknown
\stopbuffer

\typebuffer

\getbuffer

\stopsubsection

\stopsection

\stopcomponent
